<h3>Take care on country roads this Easter weekend</h3>
<p class="articlesummary">ACPOS press release - from 22-24 April
Police forces across Scotland will be focusing on motorists who
drive over the speed limit.</p>
<p class="articlebody">Association of Chief Police Officers in
Scotland (ACPOS) press release.<br />
<br />
Friday 22 April 2011 to Sunday 24 April 2011 - Police forces across
Scotland will be focusing on motorists who drive over the speed
limit.<br />
<br />
The 'Weekend of Action' co-ordinated by the Association of Chief
Police Officers in Scotland (ACPOS) is part of the Scottish Police
Service's year-round commitment to reduce the number of casualties
on our roads.<br />
<br />
The campaign is run to highlight to all road users the dangers of
speeding or driving at an inappropriate speed. Patrols in every
force area will be on the look out for motorists breaking the
law.<br />
<br />
Three out of four road deaths take place on country roads, with
speed often being a significant factor. The emphasis must be about
adapting speed to the conditions faced.<br />
<br />
As the weather improves, it is anticipated that many motorcyclists
will take to the roads, this is a particularly vulnerable group of
road users and they are urged to ride in accordance with the road
conditions.<br />
<br />
Chief Superintendent Charlie Common from Lothian and Borders Police
who is the ACPOS lead on Casualty Reduction said:<br />
<br />
'Previous days of action have shown that far too many road users
are willing to ignore speed limits and this disregard for road
safety is worrying.<br />
'Speeding offences can result in a &pound;60 fine and three penalty
points or in serious cases a report being submitted to the
Procurator Fiscal and a court appearance, which can lead to a
higher penalty being imposed.<br />
<br />
'During this campaign the eight Scottish Police Forces will be
targeting road users who continue to break the law, using marked
and unmarked police vehicles, as well as carrying out static speed
checks at identified hotspots.<br />
'Scotland has some of the U.K.'s most scenic routes and I expect
our country roads to be particularly busy over the Easter weekend.
Drivers and riders are asked to enjoy the scenery, but to exercise
due care and attention when doing so. The aim of the weekend's
campaign is to prevent accidents on our roads and to promote road
safety. Those found flouting speed limits can expect to be dealt
with appropriately.'<br />
<br />
For more information, please refer to the following websites<br />
<br />
For further information contact:<br />
ACPOS Communications<br />
0141 435 1240<br />
07771 842881<br />
communications@acpos.pnn.police.uk</p>
